1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,780
A while loop repeats a block of code as long as a specified condition is true.

2

00:00:04,780  -->  00:00:07,620
If you remember from our section on data types,

3

00:00:07,620  -->  00:00:09,720
true comes from the Boolean data type,

4

00:00:09,720  -->  00:00:11,800
which is the opposite of false.

5

00:00:11,800  -->  00:00:15,700
As such, so long as a condition is true, for example,

6

00:00:15,700  -->  00:00:19,500
so long as a number is below or equal to 100,

7

00:00:19,500  -->  00:00:21,000
counting up to 100,

8

00:00:21,000  -->  00:00:22,620
then the value is true.

9

00:00:22,620  -->  00:00:25,740
Once the number is one value over 100,

10

00:00:25,740  -->  00:00:27,575
then the condition is false.

11

00:00:27,575  -->  00:00:31,950
Let's see while loops in action with an example.

12

00:00:31,950  -->  00:00:34,545
We're going to create a counter function,

13

00:00:34,545  -->  00:00:38,260
so we're going to declare a variable called count,

14

00:00:38,260  -->  00:00:41,420
and we're going to initially set that equal to zero.

15

00:00:41,420  -->  00:00:45,630
Then we're going to write our while loop.

16

00:00:46,130  -->  00:00:49,710
To write our while loop, we'll write while,

17

00:00:49,710  -->  00:00:53,295
and then we'll use the count variable, and then we'll say,

18

00:00:53,295  -->  00:00:58,005
while that is less than five, we'll print,

19

00:00:58,005  -->  00:01:02,740
count colon, and then comma,

20

00:01:02,740  -->  00:01:05,860
write what our count variable is.

21

00:01:05,860  -->  00:01:11,160
Then we'll increment count by plus one.

22

00:01:12,770  -->  00:01:16,650
This above is an example of a counter function,

23

00:01:16,650  -->  00:01:19,730
and the way it works is that you have a number value,

24

00:01:19,730  -->  00:01:21,330
in this case, count,

25

00:01:21,330  -->  00:01:23,370
and that is initially set to zero.

26

00:01:23,370  -->  00:01:27,990
You then write a while loop here,

27

00:01:27,990  -->  00:01:32,720
where the count is less than but not equal to five.

28

00:01:32,720  -->  00:01:37,730
Then we will print the value of count with the print statement.

29

00:01:37,730  -->  00:01:46,600
The fancy plus equal one code just means add plus one to the value of the count,

30

00:01:46,600  -->  00:01:52,280
which is how it would go from zero to a value that could be up until five,

31

00:01:52,280  -->  00:01:53,620
but not including five.

32

00:01:53,620  -->  00:01:56,100
Once the value of count reaches five,

33

00:01:56,100  -->  00:01:58,660
then the function will no longer return true,

34

00:01:58,660  -->  00:02:02,445
and then the while loop would stop. Let's review.

35

00:02:02,445  -->  00:02:04,080
In this while loop example,

36

00:02:04,080  -->  00:02:07,200
the while loop states a condition that is true.

37

00:02:07,200  -->  00:02:12,890
The code will loop continue to execute while the value of the condition is true,

38

00:02:12,890  -->  00:02:16,130
in this case, the count being less than five.

39

00:02:16,130  -->  00:02:17,910
Each time the loop runs,

40

00:02:17,910  -->  00:02:24,120
count is incremented by plus one up until but not including five,

41

00:02:24,120  -->  00:02:28,050
and then the condition becomes false once it hits five,

42

00:02:28,050  -->  00:02:29,710
and then the while loop stops.

43

00:02:29,710  -->  00:02:33,470
Let's see what this looks like as we execute it.

44

00:02:33,920  -->  00:02:36,390
We'll see 0,

45

00:02:36,390  -->  00:02:37,815
1, 2,

46

00:02:37,815  -->  00:02:39,295
3, 4,

47

00:02:39,295  -->  00:02:42,150
and once count reaches five,

48

00:02:42,150  -->  00:02:44,790
then it stops, so that's why we don't see count five,

49

00:02:44,790  -->  00:02:47,080
it counts up to four.

50

00:02:47,630  -->  00:02:52,095
Pretty cool. Where do we use while loops?

51

00:02:52,095  -->  00:02:54,960
While loops are perfect for situations where

52

00:02:54,960  -->  00:02:58,660
we don't know how many iterations we need beforehand.

53

00:02:58,660  -->  00:03:01,860
This makes them incredibly useful for tasks,

54

00:03:01,860  -->  00:03:04,360
like continuously waiting for user inputs

55

00:03:04,360  -->  00:03:07,440
or processing data until a specific condition is met.

56

00:03:07,440  -->  00:03:12,000
Let's explore two practical examples that highlight the power of while loops.

57

00:03:12,000  -->  00:03:15,740
When we think about handling user inputs, in this example,

58

00:03:15,740  -->  00:03:18,340
we're going to write a while loop to continually prompt

59

00:03:18,340  -->  00:03:22,340
the user for an input until they type exit.

60

00:03:22,340  -->  00:03:24,460
How we'll do that is, we'll declare

61

00:03:24,460  -->  00:03:28,280
a variable that will be an empty string called user input.

62

00:03:31,550  -->  00:03:34,110
Then we'll write our while loop,

63

00:03:34,110  -->  00:03:39,270
and we'll say while user_input.lower

64

00:03:39,270  -->  00:03:45,700
function does not equal exit,

65

00:03:48,740  -->  00:03:51,360
we'll set user input equal to

66

00:03:51,360  -->  00:03:57,030
the input and we

67

00:03:57,030  -->  00:04:03,310
will write a multi-line comment here,

68

00:04:03,310  -->  00:04:12,600
and we'll say enter something type exit to quit the colon.

69

00:04:13,960  -->  00:04:19,790
That's all closed out. Then we will say

70

00:04:19,790  -->  00:04:27,420
print you entered followed by actually with that user,

71

00:04:27,420  -->  00:04:29,800
we'll put in right here.

72

00:04:30,680  -->  00:04:36,750
We'll close that off. The way that this loop will work is that this loop will

73

00:04:36,750  -->  00:04:42,465
keep asking the user for an input until they type exit into the input field.

74

00:04:42,465  -->  00:04:46,810
Also, notice how we're using this lower method to

75

00:04:46,810  -->  00:04:52,270
convert the user's input to a lowercase before comparing it to exit.

76

00:04:52,270  -->  00:04:55,910
This ensures that no matter how the user types exit,

77

00:04:55,910  -->  00:04:58,150
whether in upper case or mixed case,

78

00:04:58,150  -->  00:05:00,770
the loop will recognize it and stop.

79

00:05:00,770  -->  00:05:07,570
It's like having a built-in spell checker that makes sure the input is always consistent.

80

00:05:07,570  -->  00:05:11,990
This is very similar to what you will see when you

81

00:05:11,990  -->  00:05:16,510
start running a Python program or within another programming language.

82

00:05:16,510  -->  00:05:23,090
There might be a command to control plus C or to simply type exit,

83

00:05:23,090  -->  00:05:25,070
enter into your terminal,

84

00:05:25,070  -->  00:05:27,195
and the program will stop.

85

00:05:27,195  -->  00:05:30,550
Let's see what happens when we run this.

86

00:05:31,010  -->  00:05:35,950
When we run this, we'll see our comment that we'll say enter something,

87

00:05:35,950  -->  00:05:38,010
and then it'll say type exit to quit.

88

00:05:38,010  -->  00:05:40,780
If we said type something,

89

00:05:41,230  -->  00:05:43,830
we type something, say something else,

90

00:05:43,830  -->  00:05:49,755
we'll say something else, something else again.

91

00:05:49,755  -->  00:05:55,090
It's going to continually prompt us to keep writing in something into the input.

92

00:05:55,090  -->  00:05:56,950
But until we type exit,

93

00:05:56,950  -->  00:06:00,595
press ''Enter'', then it stops.

94

00:06:00,595  -->  00:06:03,190
If we were to do this again,

95

00:06:03,190  -->  00:06:10,055
let's say we even did it in all caps, it'll still exit.

96

00:06:10,055  -->  00:06:16,200
Let's say we even did some mixed upper and lower case,

97

00:06:16,200  -->  00:06:21,980
say exit, it will still always turn it to a lower case to then exit.

98

00:06:21,980  -->  00:06:30,105
That's how we combine and handle multiple user inputs in Python.

99

00:06:30,105  -->  00:06:35,715
Now, let's talk about processing data until a condition is met.

100

